  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The son of Nathan - It is uncertain whether the Nathan of this verse is the prophet or the son of David ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 5:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". While on the one hand the position of \"king's friend\" is more likely to have been held by a contemporary, which the prophet's son would have been, than by one so much younger as the son of a younger brother; on the other hand the title \"cohen\" seems to point to a member of the royal family. (See the next note.) Azariah who was \"over the officers\" was chief, that is, of the \"officers\" mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:8-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as appears from the identity of the term here used with the title by which they are designated in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Principal officer - Or, \"cohen.\" The fact that the title כהן  kôhên was borne by sons of David 2 Samuel 8:18, who could not be \"priests\" in the ordinary sense of the word, seems to identify the Nathan of this verse with David's son 2 Samuel 5:14 rather than with the prophet. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Principal officer - Or, \"cohen.\" The fact that the title כהן  kôhên was borne by sons of David ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 8:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", who could not be \"priests\" in the ordinary sense of the word, seems to identify the Nathan of this verse with David's son ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 5:14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " rather than with the prophet. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
